==Old English==

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*walo-'', from Indo-European ''*welə-'' ‘wound, injure’.

Cognate with Old Saxon ''wal-'' (in ''waldâd'' ‘murderous deed’), Old High German ''wal'', Old Norse ''val-r'' (in [[Valkyrie]], lit. ‘chooser of the slain’).

The Indo-European root is also the source of Latin [[vulnus]] ‘wound’, Old Irish [[fuil]] ‘blood’.

